rom genital tubercle, clitoris from urogenital folds, labia minora from labioscrotal swells","Labia minora from genital tubercle, labia majora from urogenital folds, clitoris from labioscrotal swells","Clitoris from genital tubercle, labia minora from urogenital folds, labia majora from labioscrotal swells","Clitoris from urogenital folds, labia minora from labioscrotal swells, labia majora from genital tubercle","Clitoris from labioscrotal swells, labia minora from genital tubercle, labia majora from urogenital folds"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eclitoris\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the genital tubercle, the \u003Cstrong\u003Elabia minora\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the urogenital folds, and the \u003Cstrong\u003Elabia majora\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the labioscrotal swells. This development occurs between weeks 9-12 of embryological development in the absence of androgens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Female external genitalia develop from the genital tubercle, urogenital folds, and labioscrotal swells in the absence of androgens","The clitoris develops from the genital tubercle, labia minora from urogenital folds, and labia majora from labioscrotal swells","Female external genitalia differentiation occurs between weeks 9-12 of embryological development"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Herrera AM, Cohn MJ. Embryonic origin and compartmental organization of the external genitalia. Scientific Reports. 2014;4(1):6896."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57854"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15917"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57854"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T10:51:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T10:5